<p>The <code>slashes</code> function adds backslashes before quotes (PHP addslashes).</p>

<h2>Basic Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}"it's here" | slashes{close}</pre>
<p>Result: <b>{"it's here" | slashes}</b></p>

<h2>Double Quotes</h2>
<pre>{open}'say "hello"' | slashes{close}</pre>
<p>Result: <b>{'say "hello"' | slashes}</b></p>

<h2>For JavaScript</h2>
<pre>var msg = '{open}'User\'s "data"' | slashes{close}';</pre>
<p>Safe JS: var msg = '<b>{'User\'s "data"' | slashes}</b>';</p>

<h2>Chained Examples</h2>
<pre>{open}'  John\'s Data  ' | trim | slashes{close}</pre>
<p>Clean and escape: <b>{'  John\'s Data  ' | trim | slashes}</b></p>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Use <code>slashes</code> when preparing strings for contexts that need escaped quotes, like JavaScript strings or certain SQL contexts (though parameterized queries are preferred for SQL).</p>
